In The Good Temp, Vicki Smith and Esther B. Neuwirth provide some novel answers to this question.Their provocative analysis is based on an insider's view of the interior dynamics of a temporary help agency in Silicon Valley. It incorporates a historical perspective on the rise of the temporary help service industry. Smith and Neuwirth document how this powerful industry not only created a new market for temporary labor but also played a fundamental role in the erosion of the permanent employment model. They analyze how agencies themselves came to manufacture and market this reinvented product-the good temp, an employee who is effective and efficient, committed, and sometimes preferable to a permanent staff member.Joining extensive participant observation data with historical analysis, The Good Temp contains some surprising findings about temporary employment today and fills a significant gap in our understanding of this important labor relationship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aTemporary employeesxUnited States. 0aTemporary employeeszUnited States. 0aTemporary employmentxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aTemporary employmentzUnited States. 0aTemporary help servicesxUnited States. 0aTemporary help serviceszUnited States. 4aBusiness (General). 4aLabor History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Labor.2bisacsh  amarket making, temporary health industry, temporary agencies, temporary employment, employment quality, modern workforce.1 aNeuwirth, Esther B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145931340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801459313423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97808014593